1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:00,962
TL;DR.

2
00:00:00,962 --> 00:00:03,087
This week in 30 seconds:.

3
00:00:03,087 --> 00:00:14,100
AI Emergency Shutdown: The US government halts Anthropic's Fable 5 & Mythos 5 via directive – three days after launch, worldwide, effective immediately.

4
00:00:14,100 --> 00:00:26,400
Siri Becomes Gemini: Apple replaces Siri's AI engine with Google Gemini; iOS 27 runs from iPhone 11 onward – EU and China remain locked out due to regulations.

5
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:40,237
IPO + Attorney General: OpenAI files an S-1 with the SEC, projecting an $85B loss for 2028 – while simultaneously receiving a subpoena from US state attorneys general.

6
00:00:40,237 --> 00:00:54,737
Prometheus Awakens: Jeff Bezos launches AI startup with $12B in capital and a $41B valuation, 150 employees – goal: develop jet engines and pharmaceuticals via AI.

7
00:00:54,737 --> 00:00:55,987
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:55,987 --> 00:01:02,387
First Documented Case: US Government Forces Emergency Shutdown of a Commercial AI Model.

9
00:01:02,387 --> 00:01:03,375
Three days.

10
00:01:03,375 --> 00:01:06,375
That's all Anthropic's most powerful model got.

11
00:01:06,375 --> 00:01:18,787
On June 9, 2026, Anthropic launched Fable 5 and Mythos 5 as the most capable models in company history – setting new records in coding, reasoning, and multimodality .

12
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:29,575
Then came June 12, 5:21 PM Eastern Time: a directive from the US Department of Commerce forced Anthropic to immediately and globally block both models .

13
00:01:29,575 --> 00:01:36,537
The government's official justification: a potential jailbreak bypass classified as a national security risk .

14
00:01:36,537 --> 00:01:52,050
From the agency's perspective, the risk calculus was clear: an uncontrolled jailbreak in an already widely deployed frontier model could be exploited by state actors – and since selective deactivation was technically impossible, only one option remained.

15
00:01:52,050 --> 00:01:57,725
Whether this assessment proportionally justifies the measures taken remains publicly unanswered.

16
00:01:57,725 --> 00:02:08,250
The technical problem is structural: Anthropic cannot selectively disable the models for specific user groups – a complete global shutdown was the only available option .

17
00:02:08,250 --> 00:02:14,262
Not only US users are affected, but all international customers and foreign employees as well.

18
00:02:14,262 --> 00:02:17,725
Mythos-class customer data is retained for 30 days .

19
00:02:17,725 --> 00:02:21,662
Anthropic complied with the directive while clearly objecting to it:.

20
00:02:21,662 --> 00:02:30,600
"We disagree that finding a narrow potential jailbreak should be grounds for recalling a commercial model distributed to hundreds of millions of people."

21
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:33,987
— Anthropic, official statement on the government directive

22
00:02:33,987 --> 00:02:43,750
Internally, Amazon CEO Andy Jassy reportedly raised safety concerns even before the regulatory directive, as TechCrunch reported on June 13 .

23
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:51,387
Amazon is one of Anthropic's strategic cloud partners via AWS – making this dynamic particularly significant.

24
00:02:51,387 --> 00:03:02,350
Why This Affects Everyone: This is the first documented case of a US government agency stopping an already commercially deployed frontier model via an emergency directive.

25
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:18,750
This sets precedents in three dimensions: for AI export control as a regulatory instrument, for the architectural question of whether selective deactivation will become mandatory in the future, and for the liability of model providers vis-à-vis government authorities.

26
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:25,937
Anthropic had reportedly pursued a "multilayered defense strategy"  – the fact that this wasn't enough is the real signal.

27
00:03:25,937 --> 00:03:29,462
Open Questions: How long will the block remain in effect?

28
00:03:29,462 --> 00:03:33,150
Can Anthropic patch the jailbreak and apply for reinstatement?

29
00:03:33,150 --> 00:03:38,162
And: will other governments – above all the EU – use this lever as well?

30
00:03:38,162 --> 00:03:49,775
Bottom Line: If even Anthropic – the company that considers safety its core mission – cannot prevent a government emergency shutdown, AI export control has become a reality.

31
00:03:49,775 --> 00:03:51,112
More Top Stories.

32
00:03:51,112 --> 00:03:57,387
Apple Turns Siri into a Gemini App – iOS 27 for Everyone from iPhone 11.

33
00:03:57,387 --> 00:04:05,675
Apple rebuilt Siri from the ground up at WWDC 2026 – with Google Gemini as the AI engine under the hood .

34
00:04:05,675 --> 00:04:18,462
The partnership with a direct rival in the AI race is an unusual strategic move: Apple gains Gemini's reasoning capabilities, while Google gets access to over one billion active iOS devices.

35
00:04:18,462 --> 00:04:26,337
At the same time, iOS 27, iPadOS 27, and macOS 27 "Golden Gate" were announced .

36
00:04:27,262 --> 00:04:38,887
iOS 27 is the most inclusive iOS version ever: compatible from iPhone 11, with 70% faster photo display and 80% faster AirDrop transfers .

37
00:04:38,887 --> 00:04:47,462
Tim Cook said farewell at WWDC – his successor as CEO will be John Ternus, planned for September 2026 .

38
00:04:47,462 --> 00:04:56,700
However, the Gemini integration remains blocked in the EU and China for now – regulation is stalling the rollout in two of the most important markets.

39
00:04:56,700 --> 00:05:03,037
Craig Federighi put Apple's stance succinctly: "We believe privacy in AI is non-negotiable."

40
00:05:03,037 --> 00:05:08,912
– a statement that raises interesting questions in the context of a Google model at the core of the platform.

41
00:05:08,912 --> 00:05:15,912
Apple has not yet communicated details on how data processing works between iOS and Google's Gemini infrastructure.

42
00:05:15,912 --> 00:05:16,737
So What?

43
00:05:16,737 --> 00:05:22,050
For developers, Gemini-in-Siri means Apple Intelligence finally becomes usable.

44
00:05:22,050 --> 00:05:25,387
For Google: the world's largest distribution channel.

45
00:05:25,387 --> 00:05:32,050
For everyone else: which manufacturer will be next to rely on a third-party LLM instead of training their own?

46
00:05:32,050 --> 00:05:40,112
OpenAI: $852B Valuation, $85B Loss, One Attorney General Subpoena.

47
00:05:40,112 --> 00:05:57,175
OpenAI has confidentially filed an S-1 prospectus with the US Securities and Exchange Commission – one week after rival Anthropic, with Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, and JPMorgan as lead bankers, and a planned IPO in September 2026 .

48
00:05:57,175 --> 00:06:22,762
The leaked numbers are remarkably contradictory: approximately 900 million weekly active users, a valuation of $852B (March 2026) and $880B on the secondary market (April 2026)  – alongside a projected annual loss of $85B for 2028 with $122B in compute costs alone .

49
00:06:22,762 --> 00:06:29,987
At the same time, US state attorneys general led by New York served OpenAI with a subpoena just before the IPO .

50
00:06:29,987 --> 00:06:39,912
Requested: documents on advertising practices, user engagement, health data, and minors' protection – supplementing an ongoing lawsuit from Florida .

51
00:06:39,912 --> 00:06:40,737
So What?

52
00:06:40,737 --> 00:06:55,575
If the world's largest AI company at ~$900B valuation and 900 million users will still lose $85B in 2028, the key IPO question isn't "growth?" but "when does the model flip to profitability?"

53
00:06:55,575 --> 00:07:00,287
– and the answer is buried in an S-1 the public isn't allowed to see yet.

54
00:07:00,287 --> 00:07:06,512
Jeff Bezos' Prometheus: $12B for the AI Engineer of the Physical World.

55
00:07:06,512 --> 00:07:21,500
Out of stealth mode and straight into the headlines: Prometheus, founded by Jeff Bezos and Vik Bajaj (ex-Verily/Google X), has gone public with a new $12B funding round and a $41B valuation .

56
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:32,150
The goal is an "Artificial General Engineer" – AI software that fully automates the design and manufacturing of physical systems like jet engines and pharmaceutical compounds.

57
00:07:32,150 --> 00:07:35,575
Offices in San Francisco, London, and Zurich .

58
00:07:35,575 --> 00:07:41,775
The ratio is staggering: just 150 employees at a $41B valuation .

59
00:07:41,775 --> 00:07:46,200
Investors include JPMorgan, BlackRock, and Goldman Sachs.

60
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:56,212
Bezos himself predicted at the announcement "labor shortages rather than job losses": "Significant productivity in the economy is going to raise the standard of living."

61
00:07:56,212 --> 00:08:07,812
Critics point out that productivity-enhancing technologies have historically first eliminated existing jobs before new fields emerge – a transition dynamic Bezos' statement glosses over.

62
00:08:07,812 --> 00:08:17,775
The startup builds on an earlier stealth round of $6.2B (late 2025) – total capital raised amounts to approximately $18B .

63
00:08:17,775 --> 00:08:18,600
So What?

64
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:33,725
When biotech and aerospace veterans from Verily and Google X join forces with Bezos capital to bet on physical AI, this is no longer a research project – it's the next industrial bet, with $41B in chips on the table.

65
00:08:33,725 --> 00:08:34,675
